This package is deisgned to help users simulate realistic datasets that reflect comm structures encountered in biological research.
Each function targets a specific class of data and allows for control over fixed effects, random effects and distributional assumptions.
The functions are intentionally modular and parameter driven to make them suitable for power analyses, simulation based inference, and for testing statistical workflows.

Most functions share some common design principles.
These being an explicit control over fixed effects, flexible random effect structures, reproducibility via a seed argument, and the option to return either a single dataset or a list of simulated datasets.

Function Overview and their usage:

simulate_seed_data_nb().

This function simulates seed production data along an elevational gradient using a negative binomial distribution.
Its key features are an elevation gradient with species-specific responses, a treatment effect (hand vs. naturally pollinated plants), species and site level random effects, and a overdispersed count data via negative binomial.
This function is more specific for what I would like to for my masters thesis, and so it is not as versatile as the others included in this package.
This function is particularily useful for testing GLMMs for count data, doing power analyses for ecological field studies, and exploring treatment x environment relationships.

simulate_binomial_data().

This function generates a binomial (survival or succes/failure) data with optional grouping and environmental gradients.
Its key features are logit-scale effects, individual-level or aaggregated binomial data, species and group random effects, and a flexible treatment structure.
This function is particularily useful for survival analysis simulations, logistic regression / GLMM testing, and for comparing individual vs. aggregated binomial models.

simulate_longitudinal_data().

This function is for simulating repeated-measures (longitudinal) data with individual travel trajectories over time.
Its key features are random intercepts and slopes per individual, an optional correlation between intercepts and slopes, treatment and time interaction effects, and group level structure.
This function is useful for mixed-effects model development, growth curve analysis, and repeated-measure experimental design.

simulate_phylo_traits().

This function simulated trait evolution along a phylogenetic tree under Brownian Motion (BM)or Ornstein-Uhlenbeck(OU) models.
Its key features are allowing for automatic or user supplied phylogenies, allowing for multiple traits, BM or OU proccesess, and an optional measurement error.
This function is useful when using comprative methods, hen doing phylogenetic signal testing, and for trait evolution modeling.

simulate_community_matrix().

This function generates species by site community matrices alond an environmental gradient.
Its key features are Gaussian niche response curves, species-specific optima and abundances, poisson or negative binomial distributions, and an option to toggle zero inflation.
This function is useful for community ecology analyses, Ordination and diversity metrics, and for testing species distribution models.

simulate_multivariate_traits().

This function simulate multivariate trait datasets with covariance structure.
Its key features is having multiple covariated traits, custom covariance or correlation matrices, environmental and treatment effects, and a optional group-level random effect.
This function is useful for multivariate analysis like PCA and MANOVA, for trait correlation studies, and for testing of covariance estimation methods.

simulate_spatial_data().

This function simulates spatially autocorrelated data using a Gaussian random field.
Its key features are using spatial coordinates (generated or supplied), its distance based covariance structure, environmental gradients, and control of spatial autocorrelation.
This function is useful for testing autocorrelation handling, when doing spatial statistics, and for geostatistical modeling.


simulate_zero_inflated_data().

This function simulates zero-inflated count data with seperate processes for counts and excess zeroes.
Its key features are a dual process model (count + zero inflation), poisson or negative binomial counts, covariates affecting both processes, and an optional group level random effect.
This function is useful for zero inflated or hurdle models, for ecological count data with excess zeroes, and for model comparison and diagnostics.
